               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000056b-2"> Three-Gate Tower was built in the first year of the
                        <term ref="/keyword/k00082">Tang</term> dynasty Ruyi reign period (692). Due
                     to its long history, it was significantly damaged, leaving only stone columns
                     buried underground. The restored structure consists of 12 sandstone pillars,
                     each with a width of 0.6 meters and a length of 5.16 meters, engraved with
                     various texts, scriptures, and figures. </p>
                  <p source="#bibl000056b-3"> From the reconstructed floor plan, the tower would
                     have originally spanned five bays in width and two bays in depth. Stairways
                     leading up to the platform are symmetrically positioned on the north and south
                     sides, directly facing the central bay. The tower had a single-eaves hip-gable
                     roof (<term ref="/keyword/k000185">shaliangtou 厦兩頭</term> or <term
                        ref="/keyword/k000143">xieshanding 歇山頂</term>), with stone columns used for
                     both the eave and central pillars. The spaces between the columns are connected
                     solely by stone architraves (<term ref="/keyword/k000038">lan’e 闌额</term>). </p>

                  <p source="#bibl000056b-4"> Regarding the background of the construction, the
                     inscription stated that “During the Ruyi period, the monk Ribao abandoned the
                     past life to pursue Buddhism. He went to the mountains and forests to obtain
                     pine wood and stone. Craftsmen carved the timber into beams and transformed the
                     stones into pillars. Then, they adorned the structures with red lacquer
                     carvings and paintings, constructed the main gate upon a stone foundation and
                     erected a pavilion atop the gateway.（乃亲自仗錫詣乎山林，尋高松，求巨石……三門之義其大矣哉。）</p>

               </desc>
